DH1 Final Project

I am going to input the full text of the first book I wrote in order to run some tests and do some analysis on it, namely in terms of word frequency and sentiment analysis. My initial (largely failed) attempt at this can be found here. The first step is to load some libraries that might be useful:

library(dplyr)
library(tidytext)
library(gutenbergr)

The process of unnesting tokens:

themuse_df <- tibble(line = 1:51, text = themusechs)
themuse_df
themuse_df %>% unnest_tokens(word, text)
themust_unnest <- themuse_df %>% unnest_tokens(word, text)

Word frequency tests

themust_unnest %>% count(word, sort = TRUE)
themust_unnest <- themust_unnest %>% anti_join(stop_words)
Joining, by = "word"
themust_unnest %>% count(word, sort = TRUE)

Elena is the protagnoist of the novel; Edouard, Warner, Kitty, and Antoine are all major characters. However, there are interesting insights to be found from some of the other results. ‘Eyes’ is the 5th most frequent word. Hands, smiles, and time are also used a lot. ‘Don’t’ and ‘take’ are the most frequent verbs. I am not excited that ‘it’s’ is used so much. I will have to think about that during the rewrite. It seems that, judging by this data alone, the book is much more positive than negative. At least, there are more negative words used, but the positive words used are used more frequently and are considered to be more positive. That’s a bit of a surprise to me, but this analysis is on a word-by-word basis.

  filter(sentiment == "negative")

wordcounts <- themuse_df %>%
  group_by(line) %>%
  summarize(words = n())

themuse_df %>%
  semi_join(bingnegative) %>%
  group_by(line) %>%
  summarize(negativewords = n()) %>%
  left_join(wordcounts, by = c("chapter")) %>%
  mutate(ratio = negativewords/words) %>%
  filter(line != 0) %>%
  top_n(1) %>%

Breaking the text down by sentences and graphing by chapter

themusesent <- themuse_df %>% unnest_tokens(sentence, text, token = "sentences")
themusesent
sentbych <- themusesent %>%
  group_by(line) %>%
  mutate(sentence_num = 1:n(),
         index = round(sentence_num / n(), 2)) %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, sentence) %>%
  inner_join(get_sentiments("afinn")) %>%
  group_by(line, index) %>%
  summarise(sentiment = sum(value, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  arrange(desc(sentiment))
Joining, by = "word"
ggplot(sentbych, aes(index, factor(line, levels = sort(unique(line), decreasing = TRUE)), fill = sentiment)) +
        geom_tile(color = "white") +
        scale_fill_gradient2() +
        scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::percent, expand = c(0, 0)) +
        scale_y_discrete(expand = c(0, 0)) +
        labs(x = "Chapter Progression", y = "Chapter") +
        ggtitle("Sentiment by Chapter") +
        theme_minimal() +
        theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
              panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
              legend.position = "top")

ggsave("test3.png", units="in", width=8, height=7, dpi=300)

I really like this graph! It’s interesting to track which chapters start more negatively or positively, where they fall in the middle, and how they end.

library(janeaustenr)

original_books <- austen_books() %>%
  group_by(book) %>%
  mutate(linenumber = row_number(),
         chapter = cumsum(str_detect(text, regex("^chapter [\\divxlc]",
                                                 ignore_case = TRUE)))) %>%
  ungroup()

original_books

tidy_austen <- original_books %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, text)

tidy_austen <- tidy_austen %>%
  anti_join(stop_words)
Joining, by = "word"
tidy_austen %>%
  count(word, sort = TRUE)

Again, ‘time’ appears. Austen’s top words are more location- and character-based.

Just for fun, I thought I would use this tutorial to look into how I am representing gender in my text.

bigrams <- themuse_df %>%
  unnest_tokens(bigram, text, token = "ngrams", n = 2, collapse = FALSE)

bigrams_separated <- bigrams %>%
  separate(bigram, c("word1", "word2"), sep = " ")

he_she_words <- bigrams_separated %>%
  filter(word1 %in% c("he", "she"))

he_she_counts <- he_she_words %>%
  count(word1, word2) %>%
  spread(word1, n, fill = 0) %>%
  mutate(total = he + she,
         he = (he + 1) / sum(he + 1),
         she = (she + 1) / sum(she + 1),
         log_ratio = log2(she / he),
         abs_ratio = abs(log_ratio)) %>%
  arrange(desc(log_ratio))

he_she_counts

Visualizing that chart:

library(ggplot2)
library(readr)
library(scales)

he_she_counts %>%
  filter(!word2 %in% c("himself", "herself"),
         total>= 9) %>%
  group_by(direction = ifelse(log_ratio > 0, 'More "she"', "More 'he'")) %>%
  top_n(15, abs_ratio) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(word2 = reorder(word2, log_ratio)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(word2, log_ratio, fill = direction)) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(x = "",
       y = "Relative appearance after 'she' compared to 'he'",
       fill = "",
       title = "Verb and gender usage") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = c("4x", "2x", "Same", "2x"),
                     breaks = seq(-2, 1)) +
  guides(fill = guide_legend(reverse = TRUE))

ggsave("verbusage.png", units="in", width=8, height=7, dpi=300)

There’s a ton of interesting stuff here. I am ashamed to find that the verb most often used with ‘she’ is ‘can’t’–this is only made better by the fact that the second-most used verb is ‘can.’ Women cry a lot more than men in this text (though I often used ‘cries’ as in ‘says with emotion’ and not ‘cries actual tears’). I am also painting a negative portrayal of men, as the most common verb associated with ‘he’ is ‘shouts.’ ‘He’ seems to be followed by a lot of speaking verbs (‘said,’ ‘grumbles,’ ‘answers,’ ‘mumbles,’ etc.). It seems like–according to this data alone–I am portraying women as more passive (shown by the frequence of words like ‘lets,’ ‘hears,’ and ‘watches’) and men as more active, talkative, and angry. This is definitely something I want to consider (and change) during my rewrites.

Some more quick work with bigrams:

musebigrams <- themuse_df %>%
  unnest_tokens(bigram, text, token = "ngrams", n = 2)

musebigrams %>% count(bigram, sort = TRUE)

musebisep <- musebigrams %>%
  separate(bigram, c("word1", "word2"), sep = " ")

bigrams_filtered <- musebisep %>%
  filter(!word1 %in% stop_words$word) %>%
  filter(!word2 %in% stop_words$word)

bigram_counts <- bigrams_filtered %>%
  count(word1, word2, sort = TRUE)

bigram_counts %>%
  filter(!word1 %in% "elena")

These bigrams were interesting but were dominated by Elena, the main character, so I filtered her name out of the first word. ‘Le repaire’ is the name of a major location, so that makes sense that it’s mentioned most frequently as a bigram. A lot of the bigrams are characters’ names and/or titles, like Madame Pavard and Ms Wise. The bigrams that most interest me here are ‘Elena’s eyes,’ ‘Warner sighs,’ ‘I’m afraid,’ and ‘God Elena,’ which is a kind of surprising one.

Lastly, I would like to look at some bigrams specific to characters and other words.

In conclusion, I have learned a lot of things about my little book. ‘Elena’ is used a lot–perhaps too much. The analysis on gender was particularly enlightening. I have a lot of things to consider as I move into the rewrite process next semester, and I hope that the next time I run these tests, I am a lot happier with the results.
